# Marketplace Seller Webhooks

All marketplace callbacks (Eneba, Gamivo, G2A, Kinguin, Digiseller, Bamboo)
are served from this Node.js Fastify backend — **NOT** from a Supabase Edge
Function. Each marketplace has its own routes registered under `/webhooks/*`
in `src/http/routes/seller-webhook.routes.ts`, authenticated by
`createMarketplaceAuthMiddleware(<provider>)`.

## Layered architecture

The webhook stack mirrors the rest of the admin API: HTTP → Use case → Ports.

| Layer | File pattern | Responsibility |
|---|---|---|
| Route | `src/http/routes/seller-webhook.routes.ts` | Method/path/auth, parser dispatch, response shape mapping |
| Parser | `src/core/use-cases/seller-webhook/<provider>/<provider>-parser.ts` | Pure functions: validate the wire body → typed DTO; build the spec error envelope |
| Use case | `src/core/use-cases/seller-webhook/<provider>/handle-<provider>-<verb>.use-case.ts` | Business logic; orchestrates ports |
| Ports | `src/core/ports/{database, seller-key-operations, seller-domain-event, seller-listing-health, variant-unavailability}.port.ts` | Adapter contracts; only thing core can depend on |

**Forbidden** in `core/use-cases/seller-webhook/**`:
- Importing from `infra/`, `http/`, or `@supabase/*` (per `backend-admin.mdc`).
- Reading `process.env.*` directly.
- Calling Sentry directly — go through `createLogger().warn(msg, err)` /
  `.error(msg, err)` so logs and Sentry capture stay coupled.

## Authentication

Each marketplace uses one of these auth strategies, all wired in
`marketplace-auth.middleware.ts`:

| Provider | Strategy | Source of truth |
|---|---|---|
| `eneba` | Bearer token | `provider_accounts.seller_config.callback_auth_token` |
| `gamivo` | Bearer token | `provider_accounts.seller_config.callback_auth_token` |
| `g2a` | Bearer token | `provider_accounts.seller_config.g2a_callback_auth_token` |
| `kinguin` | `X-Auth-Token` header | `provider_accounts.seller_config.callback_auth_token` |
| `kinguin-buyer` | `X-Event-Secret` header | `provider_accounts.api_profile.buyer_webhook_secret` |
| `digiseller` | `X-Callback-Secret` header OR `?secret=` query | `provider_accounts.seller_config.callback_auth_token` |
| `bamboo` | `secretKey` JSON body field | `provider_accounts.seller_config.bamboo_webhook_secret` |

Comparison MUST go through `timingSafeEqual` from
`src/infra/marketplace/_shared/marketplace-http.ts`. Failures return
`401 { error: 'Unauthorized' }` regardless of provider — do not leak which
component (token missing vs token mismatch vs account missing) failed.

## Gamivo Import API — locked contract

Source of truth: **`public-api-import.pdf`** (workspace root). The contract
below is what every `/webhooks/gamivo/*` route must satisfy. Per-handler
behaviour is regression-tested by:

| Layer | Test |
|---|---|
| Parser | [test/gamivo-parser.test.ts](mdc:test/gamivo-parser.test.ts) |
| Reservation | [test/handle-gamivo-reservation.use-case.test.ts](mdc:test/handle-gamivo-reservation.use-case.test.ts) |
| Order create | [test/handle-gamivo-order.use-case.test.ts](mdc:test/handle-gamivo-order.use-case.test.ts) |
| Order get keys | [test/handle-gamivo-get-keys.use-case.test.ts](mdc:test/handle-gamivo-get-keys.use-case.test.ts) |
| Refund | [test/handle-gamivo-refund.use-case.test.ts](mdc:test/handle-gamivo-refund.use-case.test.ts) |
| Offer deactivation | [test/handle-gamivo-offer-deactivation.use-case.test.ts](mdc:test/handle-gamivo-offer-deactivation.use-case.test.ts) |
| Routes (auth + envelope) | [test/integration/routes/seller-webhook-gamivo.routes.test.ts](mdc:test/integration/routes/seller-webhook-gamivo.routes.test.ts) |

When changing **any** route, parser, or use case in the `gamivo/*` tree, the
matching test above must be updated in the same change. PR that drops a test
without keeping equivalent coverage will not pass review.

### Endpoint reference

| Method + path | Auth | Success | Errors |
|---|---|---|---|
| `GET /webhooks/gamivo` | none | `204 No Content` | — |
| `POST /webhooks/gamivo/reservation` | Bearer | `200 { reservation_id }` | `400 invalid_request`, `400 insufficient_stock`, `404 not_found` |
| `POST /webhooks/gamivo/order` | Bearer | `200 { provider_order_id, keys[], available_stock? }` | `400 invalid_request`, `404 not_found`, `409 already_fulfilled`, `410 reservation_expired`, `500 provision_failed` |
| `GET /webhooks/gamivo/order/:id/keys` | Bearer | `200 { keys[], available_stock? }` | `400 invalid_request`, `404 not_found`, `500 decrypt_failed` |
| `POST /webhooks/gamivo/refund` | Bearer | `204 No Content` | `400 invalid_request` |
| `POST /webhooks/gamivo/offer-deactivation` | Bearer | `204 No Content` | `400 invalid_request` |

### Error envelope

Every 4xx/5xx response from `/webhooks/gamivo/*` MUST use
`buildErrorResponse(code, message)` from `gamivo-parser.ts`:

```json
{ "code": "<machine_code>", "message": "<human readable>" }
```

Allowed `code` values are exactly: `invalid_request`, `not_found`,
`insufficient_stock`, `reservation_expired`, `already_fulfilled`,
`provision_failed`, `decrypt_failed`. Adding a new code requires updating
the integration test envelope assertions.

### Idempotency contract

Gamivo retries every webhook on transient errors. The handlers MUST be
idempotent in these specific ways — these are the bug-traps the regression
tests guard:

- `POST /order` with a `reservation_id` whose status is already
  `provisioned` returns `200` with the same keys it returned originally
  (decrypted from `seller_key_provisions`). It does NOT mint a new
  provision. Only when the replay decrypt fails or no provision rows survive
  do we 409 `already_fulfilled`.
- `POST /refund` `refunded_keys_count` is **cumulative**, not a delta. A
  second notification with the same value is a no-op; an increased value
  refunds only `count - alreadyRefunded` more keys; values exceeding
  `totalProvisioned` are clamped. Repeat events are dedup'd via
  `refundEventId = "gamivo:<reservationId>:<count>"`.
- `POST /offer-deactivation` for a listing we don't have locally still
  returns `204` and emits the audit event + admin alert. Never 404.
- `POST /reservation` failure paths after a successful claim are wrapped in
  `setImmediate` so background event-emit failures cannot break the wire
  response.

### Wire types

- **`POST /reservation` request** — `product_id` (positive integer),
  `quantity` (positive integer), `unit_price` (non-negative float). The
  parser converts `unit_price` to cents via `Math.round(value * 100)`
  (`shared/pricing.floatToCents`).
- **`POST /order` request** — `reservation_id` MUST be a UUID v4 shape
  (validated by the parser); `gamivo_order_id` and `created_time` are
  non-empty trimmed strings.
- **`GET /order/:id/keys` `:id`** — must match `^[A-Za-z0-9_-]{1,128}$`.
  Anything else 400s before the use case is touched.
- **Keys array** in `200` responses — every element is
  `{ id: string, value: string, type: "text" }`. We never deliver `image`.

## Adding a new marketplace

When porting another marketplace seller webhook:

1. Write the parser as **pure functions** under
   `core/use-cases/seller-webhook/<provider>/<provider>-parser.ts`. Throw
   `class <Provider>ParseError extends Error` on every reject path. Add
   `buildErrorResponse(code, message)` matching the marketplace's spec
   envelope.
2. Each business operation gets its own `handle-<provider>-<verb>.use-case.ts`.
   Constructor-inject `IDatabase`, `ISellerKeyOperationsPort`,
   `ISellerDomainEventPort`, `IListingHealthPort`,
   `IVariantUnavailabilityPort` as needed. Use cases never `import` from
   `infra/`.
3. Register the use case in `di/tokens.ts` and `di/container.ts`.
4. Add the auth strategy (or reuse one) in
   `marketplace-auth.middleware.ts` keyed by `provider_code`.
5. Add the routes to `seller-webhook.routes.ts` under `/webhooks/<provider>`
   with `preHandler: [createMarketplaceAuthMiddleware('<provider>')]`. Routes
   parse, dispatch, and map use-case results to status + body — **no
   business logic**.
6. Write the four test families before merging:
   - `test/<provider>-parser.test.ts` — every accept and reject path of
     every parser, plus `buildErrorResponse` shape.
   - `test/handle-<provider>-<verb>.use-case.test.ts` — one per use case.
     Use the shared stubs in [test/helpers/gamivo-test-stubs.ts](mdc:test/helpers/gamivo-test-stubs.ts)
     as a template (or import directly when the port surface matches).
   - `test/integration/routes/seller-webhook-<provider>.routes.test.ts` —
     route mapping, auth (401 on missing/bad token), parser → 400 envelope
     shape, and any health probe endpoint.
   - Pin the spec sample bodies from the marketplace's PDF/docs verbatim in
     parser fixtures so future spec drift forces an explicit test update.

### Test stubs — DO and DON'T

- **DO** implement every method on the port interface in your stub. Type
  it as `class StubFoo implements IFoo` so a port-method addition fails
  compile-time, not just at runtime.
- **DO** use `vi.fn()` plus `mockResolvedValue` defaults in stub
  constructors, so tests that don't care about a method don't trip on
  `undefined.then`.
- **DO** assert on `db.updates` / `db.inserts` arrays for SQL writes — see
  `TableStubDatabase` in `test/helpers/gamivo-test-stubs.ts`.
- **DO** call `flushSetImmediate()` before asserting on background events
  emitted via `setImmediate`.
- **DON'T** reuse `test/helpers/mock-ports.ts` `MockDatabase` for webhook
  tests — it's missing several `IDatabase` methods (`updateIn`,
  `upsertMany`, `invokeFunction`, `invokeInternalFunction`, `queryAll`,
  `insertMany`) and is meant for the auth-mocking integration suite.
- **DON'T** use `as any` or `as unknown as` to short-circuit a missing port
  method — extend the stub.
